– 2 –
1 healthcare, security, hospitality, education and law enforcement, is
2 essential for the early identification and correction of any gaps in
3 reporting;
4 WHEREAS, This State seeks to establish a more robust legal
5 framework to protect victims of human trafficking, mitigate the
6 challenges associated with victim participation in criminal
7 proceedings, prosecute offenders and provide a comprehensive
8 support system through leveraging existing resources and exploring
9 new resources;
10 WHEREAS, Convening stakeholders to study, strategize,
11 prioritize and openly identify and implement best practices in
12 successful anti-human trafficking frameworks from across the
13 nation will ensure that a robust and cost-effective regulatory system
14 exists for those involved in tracking, investigating and protecting
15 victims of human trafficking; now, therefore, be it
16 RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE STATE OF NEVADA, THE
17 ASSEMBLY CONCURRING, That the Joint Interim Standing
18 Committee on the Judiciary is hereby directed to conduct an interim
19 study concerning human trafficking during the 2025-2026
20 legislative interim; and be it further
21 RESOLVED, That the study must include, without limitation, an
22 examination of:
23 1. The current legal and systemic processes relating to human
24 trafficking in this State, including an in-depth assessment of the
25 current statutory and regulatory structure from both the criminal
26 justice and human welfare perspectives;
27 2. The current programs, services and needs of the Division of
28 Child and Family Services of the Department of Health and Human
29 Services regarding any duties assigned to the Division or
30 Department, such as the statewide plan for the delivery of services
31 to victims of human trafficking, the resources and needs of the State
32 of Nevada Human Trafficking Coalition, the current data collection
33 and reporting status regarding human trafficking under the Center
34 for the Analysis of Crime Statistics within the Department of
35 Criminal Justice at the University of Nevada, Las Vegas and a
36 review of the Account for Victims of Human Trafficking
37 administered by the Department of Health and Human Services,
38 including any pilot programs established thereunder that provide
39 alternatives to law enforcement responses to victims of human
40 trafficking;
41 3. The resources, policy needs, commonalities and
42 divergencies of interested stakeholders, including, without
43 limitation, the State of Nevada Human Trafficking Coalition, the
44 Nevada Coalition to Prevent the Commercial Sexual Exploitation of
45 Children, the Nevada Policy Council on Human Trafficking, each
-
